d-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Tyskland"},"nl":{"1158–1230":"1158–1230","1170–1218":"1170–1218","1195–1269":"1195–1269","1134–1182":"1134–1182","1138–1182":"1138–1182","1138":"1138","1269":"1269","1158":"1158","1134":"1134","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1218":"1218","Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Duitsland","Arberg, Kohn, Germany":"Arberg, Landkreis Ansbach, Bayern, Duitsland","Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Duitsland"},"en":{"1158–1230":"1158–1230","1170–1218":"1170–1218","1195–1269":"1195–1269","1134–1182":"1134–1182","1138–1182":"1138–1182","1138":"1138","1269":"1269","1158":"1158","1134":"1134","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1218":"1218","Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Arberg, Kohn, Germany":"Arberg, Ansbach, Bavaria, Germany","Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Molsberg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Sven, Bjorn, Ludvig.  German Bernhard, Kurt.  Jewish Chaya, Herschel, Hyman.","Swedish: ornamental name composed of the elements <i>mosse</i> ‘peat bog’ + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial extension of   Moses  , with German <i>Berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mossburg","meanings":["Possibly also an Americanized form of German <b>Mosberg</b>, see   Mossberg  .","Americanized form of German <b>Maasberg</b>, unexplained."]},{"name":"Moses","meanings":["Jewish, Welsh, African American, and African (mainly Nigeria): from the Biblical personal name borne by the Israelite leader who led the Israelites out of Egypt, as related in the Book of Exodus. The Hebrew form of the name is   Moshe  . It is probably of Egyptian origin, from a short form of an ancient Egyptian personal name such as <i>Rameses</i> or <i>Tutmosis</i>, meaning ‘conceived (by a god)’. However, very early in its history the name acquired a folk etymology, being taken as a derivative of the Hebrew root verb <i>mshh</i> ‘extract or draw (something), e.g. from water’ and was associated with a story of the infant Moses being discovered among the bullrushes by Pharaoh's daughter (Exodus 2: 1-10). As a Welsh surname, it was adopted among Dissenter families in the 18th and 19th centuries. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Italian   Moise  , Hungarian <b>Mózes</b> (see   Mozes  ), Assyrian/Chaldean   Moshe  , Arabic   Musa  .","English: variant of   Moss  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: variant of <b>Moyses</b>, a Cornish personal name derived from Middle English <i>Moises</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Moses</i> (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"und","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Klaus, Otto, Wilhelm.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Mund(e)</i>, in many cases representing Old English <i>Munda</i>, a pet form of names like <i>Ēadmund</i> (Middle English <i>Edmund</i>, common in East Anglia). In northern and eastern England the equivalent Old Norse <i>Mundi</i> (a pet form of names like <i>Agmundr</i>) would also have given rise to Middle English <i>Mund(e)</i>.","German: variant of   Mundt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Monday","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Mundi</i>, <i>Mundy</i>, usually a pet form of male personal names ending in <i>-mund</i> or <i>-mond</i> (see   Mund  , and compare   Edmond  ,   Hammond  , and   Simmonds  ). Alternatively, and especially in northern and eastern England, the name might derive from Old Norse <i>Mundi</i>, a pet form of names like Old Norse <i>Agmundr</i>, Middle English <i>Agemund</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>Mone(n)day</i> ‘Monday’. It is possibly a name given to one born on that day or to a holder of <i>Mondayland</i>, land held on condition of working for the lord on Mondays."]},{"name":"Mundt","meanings":["German:","nickname for someone with a prominent or striking mouth or whose mouth was in some other way remarkable, from Middle High German <i>munt</i> ‘mouth’.","nickname for a guardian or trustworthy person, from Middle High German <i>munt</i> ‘guardian, protector’."]},{"name":"Munson","meanings":["English (mainly Essex): patronymic from the personal name   Mund  , meaning ‘son of Mund’. See also   Munn  .","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish   Monsen  . Compare   Munsen  .","Altered form of   Monson   1, a surname of Swedish origin."]}]},{"name":"Adelheid","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heid</i> ‘sort, kind’.  See also  <b>Adelaide</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adelheid von Molsberg und Freusberg was born in 1158, in Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany, her father, Anselm III. VON MOLSBERG, was 24 and her mother, Hedwig VON KEMPENICH, was 20. She had at least 1 son with Eberhard von Arenberg. She died in 1230, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1158–1230":"1158–1230","1170–1218":"1170–1218","1195–1269":"1195–1269","1134–1182":"1134–1182","1138–1182":"1138–1182","1138":"1138","1269":"1269","1158":"1158","1134":"1134","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1218":"1218","Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Arberg, Kohn, Germany":"Arberg, Landkreis Ansbach, Bayern, Saksamaa","Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1158–1230":"1158–1230","1170–1218":"1170–1218","1195–1269":"1195–1269","1134–1182":"1134–1182","1138–1182":"1138–1182","1138":"1138","1269":"1269","1158":"1158","1134":"1134","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1218":"1218","Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksa","Arberg, Kohn, Germany":"Arberg, Landkreis Ansbach, Bayern, Saksa","Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksa"},"fr":{"1158–1230":"1158–1230","1170–1218":"1170–1218","1195–1269":"1195–1269","1134–1182":"1134–1182","1138–1182":"1138–1182","1138":"1138","1269":"1269","1158":"1158","1134":"1134","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1218":"1218","Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne","Arberg, Kohn, Germany":"Arberg, Landkreis Ansbach, Bayern, Allemagne","Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Molsberg, Westerwaldkreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Adelheid von Molsberg und Freusberg est née en 1158, à Molsberg, Nochern, Rhein-Lahn-Kreis, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne, son père, Anselm III. VON MOLSBERG, avait 24 ans et sa mère, Hedwig V